Romanian "toamna" name for "autumn" etymologically comes from Spanish/Portugal "te amo" (I love you), because in the autumn's growing darkness, we uncover our love to one another before cold death's face and finally seize courage to confess our feelings openly under the solstice.
You will notice "I love you" in the above post is not inside quotation marks, because it is not a translation of the already famous Spanish phrase, but a direct message to The Girl Reading This.

Joke aside, the official Romanian etymology tracing it to Latin "autumnus" is nonsense, true origin is Bulgarian word for "dark", namely "tamen", because autumn is when it starts to get the most dark. The solstice already is the darkest point and thus triumphant for light cometh.

Mentioned this in a comment recently, but remember with cheese one of the most important things to look for is real animal rennet instead of microbial rennet used in worse quality ones. Cottage cheese has high Phosphate/Calcium ratio so good to have it together w/ milk to balance

Parmesan seems one of the safest options if you're an American, the Norwegian brown cheese I mentioned a few times after a friend bought it also has high Phosphate low Calcium so it's similar to cottage cheese in that regard (as is literally any other food with such a P/C ratio).
